The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great shock last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of all that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence predicted the standard model: our best or “less bad” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But it’s not entirely clear to physicists that it’s about Higgs.
We know without a doubt that there is a new particle and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data revealed this week at an important physics conference held in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still needed to be completely safe.
Anyway, we assume it's Higgs, because the chances of being wrong seem to be low.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to break that rule and don’t try too hard, because it will end up hurting.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" consisting, grossly, of some of its characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we meet the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And on the other are the bosons, a dirty panda of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratories’ website The Particle Adventure, which, by the way, is extraordinary, the bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, of which we will not talk here, and the "particles of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be in any way.
These bosons, you might point out here, are not the exotic bugs we might believe.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or "light particle" that acts as the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disorders" the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (of light, of infrared, of ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, however, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it you need to reach extremely high energies, a bit like an iced pond in which only a thick rock could slide over the surface.
That’s why it takes an immense particle accelerator like CERN’s (the big Hadron Collider is a 27 km ring of circumference!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stand by itself stuck to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), don’t have it.
