This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation regarding gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we have not found such differences in CERN so far.
Repercussions
The impact of such research on our day-to-day lives is difficult to predict, but we don’t think we’re wrong to say it won’t have any.
For them to see: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in laboratories did not at all suspect the revolution their work would provoke.
They were going through the scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked in the Bell labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, initially the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Imagine...
