In it, bitcoin was described as “the most successful virtual currency”, “competition with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other systems with virtual currency types such as "credits", used to advance in a video game and which can be earned by playing or can be bought (and even sometimes redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both depositors of accounting books, verifiers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes consist of the public account book, which is spread throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a kind of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a file shredding phase, i.e., transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique numeric footprint.
Computers "pick up" the new transaction and add a number before "swiping" the set.
The goal is to find the number that a particular footprint offers (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the good one.
The transaction is then indestructiblely linked to the set chain of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, one user would pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphaned, as both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is split into two regularly, most likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by up to one hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in every increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in deposit.
“The ruling used does not affect the same protocol,” said Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the possibilities of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash presents the same defect.
