Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, of the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the accounting book and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the "Giant Cuts" were released.
“$30,000 has been exchanged,” said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes quite a bit in the potential of this technology in addition to in the transaction network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus come out cheaper.
The carrier also manages its identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to start up in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
Simply provide an address that a phone can “photograph and recognize,” says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take a while for Bitcoin to be imposed, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicts.
Moreover, in its report the ECB plans to reassess the various risks, now considered high, should this currency succeed.
