Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much “paper” that those who want to look for failures in the system will be able to do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as they are now.
You talk about the problems of our country with the transfer of legislation regulating the practice of public procurement.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is it an office similar to our NK<0xC3><0x9A> or is it organized in another way?
As for the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, there acts the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Accounts), with an organization similar to ours, with a school also, the only thing is that in its case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
Competences are also somewhat analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organization, the courts of accounts are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, which here we call state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled in the Federal Court of Accounts.
As far as local law is concerned, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would not like to establish a comparison without specific data; however, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be precisely specified in what is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
That's certainly not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make these kind of comparisons.
It must be said that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it wasn't, it wouldn't be any benefit for them to collaborate with our office, would it?
As for the legislation of our country, what did the amendment to the law on public awards mean for your Office? Is it any indication of its impact?
Considering that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet appeared in the control proceedings.
Since we perform ex post checks, you need to have a certain delay.
For now, it is noted in the process of preparing future controls: we have started a new tool for "non-economic risk detection", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are changed, the conditions of some types of selection process are corrected.
Do you think that the adoption of this law is beneficial, or rather, that it is a stumbling block for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that can arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and each law not respected in terms of public awards meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal decision, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only be able to create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We’ll see where this path starts.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA0>varc system, referring to the fact that they are autonomous only on paper.
Is the svarc system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits anything, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the Office from acting that has an obligation to carry out such checks and require obligations.
You can say, "We change the law and we allow it," but you can't say we'll do it like nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the legislation is quite strict as to how it should be formally acted, and this is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate is excluded with the best offer for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
