Poland and the Cosmos.
At the meeting of Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency last week Poland was accepted as the twelfth member of ESA. It is the second member of ESA of the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began an intense collaboration with ESA in 1994 and during the following years participated in the Agency’s project commission.
However, Poland’s path to the cosmos began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already engaged in space flights before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld’s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory in which, on December 6, 1933, he presented his ideas on the pioneering study “Introduction to Cosmonautics”.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the attendees indifferent and, years later, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his "Introduction to the Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, he was known all over the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when he put his name on one of the craters of the moon's hidden face.
Already in 1925 a drawer was built in Poland that was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, it is not known who was the author of the proposal and the details of the project are also not known.
It is not clear whether the rocket would be used for start-up or braking.
Information about this dressin is limited to the collection in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the missiles.
The research was funded by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved material, it becomes clear that the research reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric hunting missile designed by engineer Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the study "Rakieta - torpedo powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all missile technology projects for military use and coordinated all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the start of the war.
Other studies dedicated to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautze).
In the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, reference is made for the first time to society with four very extensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, Prof. M. Subotowicze proposed the creation of a society dedicated to cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with prospects for the future.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronautics (PTA) aspired to be part of the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951) and in the fall of that same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became the vice president of the International Astronautics Federation.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Beginning in 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the RM rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research was carried out.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957 and was first launched on October 10, 1958.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and did not reach 5 kg in weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in the summer of 1959 air tests of the two-stage RM-2 rockets began in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>d<0xC3><0xB3>w desert.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a 14.5 km apogee and its mission would be to control the high wind.
However, in 1962 the works were suspended.
The successor to the first RM rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other by the available space for scientific apparatuses.
In the Meteor-1A the available space for volume was 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and in the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum peak in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, the first air tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful weight of 10 kg up to 60 km in height.
Later, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also necessary to mention the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national committee of COSPAR two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the space research on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
The suspension of the Social Work Act is not the solution.
Last week the Constitutional Court suspended the Social Work Act.
The resolution sparked a heated debate in society.
It will certainly be interesting to examine the existing problem from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as in the globalised world, are based on the principle of greater economic competition and less normative.
Consequently, this means that the different economic forms and national economic systems are in permanent conflict with each other.
The cause lies in the principle of free trade and the free and unlimited movement of private capital, along with unbridled financial speculation.
The effect of the large differences in labour costs (of wages) creates economic tensions.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the situation in which the manufacturer, with the import of cheap goods, tries to shorten distances and for this purpose "provokes a drop" in the price of the competitor with the aim of making itself with the most part of the market and thereby increasing its profit margin.
Large-scale means, for most entrepreneurs, moving production abroad, buying there cheaper or disappearing. The result is high unemployment in those countries where the price of labor, compared to other economies, is higher.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and, therefore, is not responsible for the unemployment that this phenomenon generates, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
This whole situation leads to the total disinterest of entrepreneurs in paying taxes and compensating for the economic and social damage they have caused in their pursuit of profit.
The situation is universally so well known that it is not necessary to present concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create situations, in certain economies, in which the governments of these countries are forced to compete with the aim of artificially reducing the social level of the population itself and thus attracting foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments make private capital available to their own population without taking into account the social decline.
This is especially evident in the changes in the laws in force.
The goal is to force the population to accept the dictates of private capital, especially as regards wages.
This takes place, on the one hand, through the system of economic obligation in the case of long-term unemployment; on the other hand, through the restricted right of employees in terms of labour rights.
The result is growing poverty along with increasing differences between the poor and the rich.
For a number of years, there have been food delivery points in Germany for poor people who cannot sustain themselves with their own work.
The number of people receiving this type of assistance has reached a million.
Within the framework of the increased competitiveness of the German economy, there is a fairly frequent case: people employed with a salary so low that the state must pay the rest to reach the minimum necessary to survive.
A scandal of this kind related to the situation of auxiliary employees of the German federal parliament was made public.
The austerity measures of virtually all southern EU states lead, without a doubt, to the same situation. People, pressed by an abysmal decline of their social level, are forced to emigrate as in the 19th century or to mallive with a terrible wage at the limit of society, hoping that one day the country will be deprived of its capital.
Is it necessary to ask where it comes from?
In the case of other EU countries, then poverty passes from one country to another or never arrives, as Chinese, Indians, Brazilians, Turks, Moroccans, Egyptians or Africans continue to work for a tiny fraction of a European wage.
This also affects all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media claim to the satire that the state should not bring capital to the economy, that leading the economy leads to its failure.
Private capital defends with nails and teeth the thesis that the state should not intervene in the economy by interfering in control.
Next, it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence with its selfishness in the political march and, therefore, throughout the state.
In this case, the answer is clearly affirmative.
The proof is the existence of lobbies, in practice very powerful and omnipresent, in all states.
The result is a desperate situation that manifests itself in the field of corruption, in mutual favours, in legislation that is practically reprehensible everywhere but not punishable.
In Germany, the situation is as follows: the state ministries, in the absence of financial means, entrust the drafting of bills to private law firms, which are often linked to the industry.
This type of bill is then passed in the Bundestag, the German parliament.
In this way, all power does not emanate from the people, as announced in the constitutions of Western democracies, but from the strong financial groups that represent their own interests.
It is obvious that democracies with a liberal orientation quickly find themselves in a situation like the one described by Appianos in his The Crisis of the Roman Republic in the Times of Caesar and Pompeii: "The state took time to disintegrate and the administrations dealt with force."
In exchange for bribes, favors obtained illegitimately and help to fund stones or swords.
The bribery and corruption spread unimpeded, and the people came to the polls with the vote applauded in advance." "There were no people in character who aspired to a position in the administration, so once, because of this disorganization, the state was in a state of mind, and it was in a state of mind that was in a state without consuls."
The conclusion, as in ancient times, is that society today is based on disregarding preferences of individual benefit without taking into account common interests.
Private capital is not able, at its core, to understand and claim the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is the same as then, an unprecedented decline of the elite, without any effort to reform it in depth.
The causes of the rise of the fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the unbridled liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
