The MVRDV architecture study shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the recently completed "mountain of books" - 2 photos
“I think the building is fun, it has a futuristic look, and finally there’s something interesting to see,” says Lisette Verhaig, a street passerby.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: “Furthermore, the building is beautiful.”
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
No one likes to go into those old-fashioned libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town located at the gates of Rotterdam that barely deserves a fleeting visit, boasts the dubious honor of rising with a record to forget.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counter this shameful situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute in some way to the general culture and copy the seven fictitious bridges that appear represented in the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so it was as the political leaders decided that there was only one possibility to improve the statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, from the Dutch architecture studio MVRDV, a master in the art of bar charts and responsible for fun buildings besides cynics, took the subject with his usual serenity and appeared at the presentation of the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And as the jury looked perplexly around him and shrugged, Maas proceeded to pile up the books by size forming a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here you have it, my proposal for the Spijkenisse mountain of books, the so-called <0x60>Boekenberg'."
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain rises at its intended location.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of residential and townhouse buildings.
In early November, the mountain of books was awarded the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town lacking history, which to date had nothing but a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade one would rather intuit a milk plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Way to the Book
The first impression is that it is a book paradise under a quesera.
It is true that there is an elevator that transports us right to the center of this mountainous massif, but the true lovers of space and reading do not use it, but prefer to merge with its topography every step of its climb to the top.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to embrace with the view, the padded brick floor and the elegant headlights unequivocally support the public condition of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
By raising the view you can get to view the park benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Usually bookshelves are arranged along the facade and in the center a huge dark room opens up which is usually something uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
What we have done is to put the classic spatial configuration on top and take out the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention deserve the black shelves that assume the functions of wall cladding, parapet and railing at the same time.
The sight, the touch and the smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unknown material.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” explains Joop Trouborst, head of the project in the city of Spijkenisse.
And so it is like one day, in a fresh agricultural holding, we come across the appropriate by-product from agriculture.
For many years, in the greenhouses and in the fields of the Netherlands, a plastic fabric of a few millimeters thick has been used as a base to hold the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine tissue lasts for two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library, this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to obtain four centimetres thick planks.
With heat and pressure, the so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material that smells like a new car mix and sports shoe.
After 105 steps it reaches the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain awaits us the reward: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but in it you can also enjoy tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant ambience in pairs that maintain the appropriate atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a New Soul
“Although it is hard to believe given its large glazed surfaces, this building is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” Trouborst points out.
The necessary heating and cooling are obtained from geothermal energy.
Despite the fact that the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunnier days the sun only shines for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden enclosures located in a transverse direction to the glass facade serve to give shade and absorb most of the sun’s rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is a matter of automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical worker in the information technology sector, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
