Szabo: "Germans must play a more prominent role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-Europe relations, this puts Berlin in a rather pelicit diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany understood that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories the status of an observer state of the United Nations.
However, Berlin finally abstained.
- Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the special relationship that unites the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about establishing a no-fly zone.
This was finally declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, it is.
This is because he is currently reorienting his foreign policy, moving away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes it even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but are not used to doing so.
I think they’re still figuring out what their role will be, but they’ve already begun the road to a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Great Britain.
What does “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy finds a strong motivation in economic policy, that is, in exports and in their relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position taken in relation to the conflict in the Middle East and in the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, he must be careful and not alienate himself from the Arab public opinion, nor from the Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn't give it that much importance since it's not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the U.S. by abstaining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not think there has been such a drastic break-up as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps Germany has managed to achieve a certain degree of respect.
After all, all this has only been done to demonstrate that it is a country that they take seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the U.S. has clearly shown itself in favor of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the U.S. and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of American domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration secretly shows a great understanding of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot publicly defend that position.
I believe that the true disparity of opinions does not actually have the scope that is attributed to them.
If we look at relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is by no means enthusiastic about the policy he develops.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that’s exactly what makes it so difficult for Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a higher entity, but they must push things from their own position.
That is exactly what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will assume a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European position.
Of course this is not easy for Germany, either simply because of the relationship it maintains with Israel.
This has always been a pilgrim issue.
But I think the Germans are clear that they must play the role of an independent figure.
Does Germany see itself in the role of an important international actor? Does Germany really want to take on a leading role?
Or is it still hard for you to accept that leadership?
Germany has not yet become accustomed, it is always something uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country continues to have a more important role to play.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany positions itself as the main actor, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and no one wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
In this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It must show a receptive attitude towards different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
U.S. influence in European politics is decreasing more and more, but the EU is not currently covering that gap, so who is left?
The Germans will have no choice but to take on a more prominent role.
Even if they don’t like it, if they find it unpleasant or if it makes them an even more unpopular people, it’s life!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly analyze the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a well-known brand worldwide and Polo Ralph Lauren as well.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name is hidden a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponyms do not file a lawsuit.
And even then it is not clear that they will be given the right.
“Foreigners find it increasingly difficult to protect their brands in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at the Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to record their marks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada is registered Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way as the sports goods manufacturer Puma has.
Pattloch opens an archive where he holds seats at the Beijing trademark office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company applied to register the brand Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In the big cities there are large warehouses of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are of a different nature. On behalf of his clients, he fights against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a denomination that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or companion brand.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It refers to women who have "fished" a rich man.
Chinese authorities are not to blame.
“It’s harmful to the business, we have to fight against it,” Pattloch demands.
“The brand makes water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage the image suffers is enormous.”
The financial losses and procedural costs of the sectors affected are multi-million dollar, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from market analysis firm CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year, China is, in size, the third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in trademark registration is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
Processes can last up to nine years and the result is uncertain.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because it had taken so long that the name in question had already become a "market reality".
“If the plaintiff is in bad luck, he may even have to pay money to the plagiarist because the lawsuit has damaged his trademark in China,” Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the most well-known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against the construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That is why today the Chinese can continue to use a very similar emblem to the Mercedes star.
The Volvo buyer, Geely, initially used a white and blue logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in the courts and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China against imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing recognizes that in 2010 they have had difficulties due to the shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the job emergency situation has returned to normal.”
In this way, the number of unprocessed claims processes has been reduced by 22%.
Nearly 57,000 of these cases were resolved, 75% more than in the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain pending for resolution.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As is usual in China, the figures are surprising.
Last year, CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
It would be a new record and means that China is leading the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, according to the brand office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, which amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan in terms of rights would have been embroiled.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as demonstrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting in the courts against a Chinese impersonator.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the impersonator has managed to secure Chinese rights over the Freudenberg brand.
“We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany the surnames are not protected,” says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the appeal of the Munichers.
In the following two instances, Freudenberg was right, but the other side is still fighting today.
You have to be very careful
The case has now reached the doors of the Superior Court of Justice, where the case remains pending.
Wentzler trusted in being able to resolve the issue favorably and praised the professionalism of the courts.
However, it also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.”
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business file has had to review records up to a hundred years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the other side a "sum of six figures in euros" with the aim of reaching a friendly agreement, but it was not successful.
“This shows how much we care,” says Wentzler.
The dangers that lurk in the Far East threaten even to affect Europe,
specifically if the impersonators there secure the rights to unprotected marks.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and skin products.
The group has long since abandoned this commercial field, however it managed to prevent registration.
“You have to be very careful,” says Wentzler.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch recommend German companies to be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international law on trademark rights, but what needs to be done is to “register also in China everything that may be susceptible to protection,” as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the topic may turn out to be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, if Freudenberg lost the last assault of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the other party license rights by his own name, as explained by Wentzler.
That or in the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
