Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
In the midst of useless and usual discussions about who started first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, the city of Jerusalem and the capital of Israel.
But, even though Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their ancient conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left it all made pieces whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been trapped in the regional turmoil.
Perhaps this will make your struggle even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to think that their lethal dead-end situation could be unleashed.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism now seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on Nov. 21, this week’s clashes have bolstered the hawks on both sides.
Hamas leaders, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has received a good blow.
And despite killing some of its leaders and putting pressure on the 1.7 million inhabitants of Gaza in one of the most miserable and populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to end Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its ruthless rivals Fatah, the most moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders could come to the conclusion that time plays in their favor.
Since Islamists have been gaining influence across the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a renaissance regional power that had previously been the closest Muslim ally to Israel, has embraced the cause of Hamas, and Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf, has also done so.
Exulting Hamas members say the Islamist half-moon is encircling Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where the Hezbollah militia party dominates, passing through Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist trend could overthrow Bashar Assad, until they reach Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Especially on the southern side of Israel, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, unlike the most populous and fundamental Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the lay despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
Instead, the Muslim Brotherhood are Hamas’ cousins and its leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, it is possible that Hamas emerges as a protagonist to which it cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, the hard wing of Israel will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel’s Iron Dome missile system has proven effective and many of Hamas’ missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep more calmly... for a while.
As for diplomacy, the United States is stronger than ever; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for starting the latest wave of violence.
First of all, Israel has prospered, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have killed some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, in part thanks to the barrier that corroborates the West Bank, the main piece of a territory aspiring to become a state of Palestine, and protects the international settlements that continue to increase despite the fact that Israel continues to expand.
Mr. Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even harder-line group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the pre-election period on 22 January, is in a good position.
Why spoil those twisted Palestinians by giving them a state of their own?
If they really ruled in the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire rockets just like their compatriots did in Gaza?
It is better to have them behind that wall and give them a good blow if they raise their heads.
Perhaps the hard wing is imposed, although the Arab spring could alter its calculations.
Although Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere do not appreciate Israel too much, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors together.
Starting a war with the region’s superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments improve their economies.
That the pragmatic Mr. Morsi has worked with Barack Obama to get the ceasefire is a good wish and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis should also think in the long run.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination means creating a powder that will one day explode in the territories occupied by Israel, just as this week it exploded a bus in Tel Aviv.
Repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demographics are making the situation worse as the Arab population increases.
The brutal missions against Gaza every two or three years to reject Hamas will pay an ever-increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution remains the one preached by sensible people on both sides, most of the outside world and this newspaper: two states and the transfer of territory by Israel for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire gives a little more impetus to the outside people who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must begin to stop the entry of weapons into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented situation to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a 1967-based Jewish state, with land swaps and a shared Jerusalem.
The Arabs outside the issue should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to unite.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain a virtual state category at the UN.
Mr. Obama also has an important role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he omitted to present his own plan for peace.
Again at the White House, it seems equally reticent to devote his attention to him.
This attitude is a deplorable vision of the future.
A stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The law of generic tobacco packaging comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and parts of the body with diseases look on boxes of a turned off green color, which are the same for all tobacco brands
Australian law on tobacco and generic packaging, a pioneer in the world, comes into force and replaces the logos and colors of the brands with a wrapper of an olive green extinguisher, scary images of parts of the body with diseases and representations of children and babies sick by being children of smoking parents.
Except for the different images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all of them printed on a small font type.
It is the strictest regime in the world for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government says the goal is to deter young people from smoking by eliminating the traits that make this habit glamorous.
Trust studies that show that if a person hasn’t started smoking before age 26, there’s a 99% chance they’ll never do it.
“It can be seen that children, even from a very early age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand,” said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that showed, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest rates of smokers in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies said the law would encourage the black tobacco market, in which cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
“The legislation will bring serious unintended consequences,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
It will increase the amount of tobacco that counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring to sell on the streets of Australia.
Other people say that their business has benefited after the passing of the law.
Sandra Ha, of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, claimed that the demand for pickups and silicone covers to cover the unpleasant images of the boxes had skyrocketed from almost zero two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan filed a lawsuit against Subacco.
She said that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale establishments and that she was expecting more stock.
“It’s a good business for us.”
According to experts, the possible obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the demographic sector to which the plan is directed.
After a series of Australian laws that ban television advertising and sports sponsorship and force most sellers not to put cigarettes on the market, tobacco marketing has gone on to be done online.
Australia has banned advertising on the Internet to local businesses and websites, but cannot restrict it to foreign pages.
“If you trade tobacco and you only have this small window left to promote your products, online space is the most compelling place to be,” said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in reviews of brands from “walking citizens” published on social media websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One wonders if it’s just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and has taken the trouble of making a video or if some marketing company is behind it all.
The British American Tobacco of Australia indicated that the industry focuses more on what involves new regulations than on marketing.
Industry has even come to pay for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to reject the new rules; these countries are claiming to the World Trade Organization that trade is being unfairly restricted, even though none of these countries have a significant trade volume with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a resolution in mid-2013.
Plibersek said the government had held talks with other countries that are considering applying similar tobacco packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to introduce the obligation to include images in the boxes.
They are currently mandatory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
In Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India, tougher laws are being considered.
In Australia, many smokers are challenging.
“The pictures don’t affect me.
I just don’t care about them.”
“Take the cigarette and keep the package,” says Victor El Hage as he buys a package with the image of a tumor in his mouth.
"Honestly, there's only one reason I'd stop smoking: for my daughter."
James Yu, the manager of the King of the Pack pond in downtown Sydney, indicates that uniform boxes make it more difficult for him to put them on the shelves.
“It usually took an hour to drop off a delivery; now it’s four,” Yu says.
“The government should have totally banned tobacco and then it’s, well, it’s over and we close the store,” he says as he raises his hands up.
In a constantly connected world, it’s not so bad to get a little bored
During this year’s Thanksgiving holidays, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on suffered a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, without forgetting us from duty-free stores.
But there are more and more academics and experts in child development who praise the goodness of boredom.
According to them, it is good that, both we and our children, we get bored from time to time.
Absurdity forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we don’t experience the benefits of boredom.
So should we accept boredom in good faith?
Yeah.
And no.
But, we'll talk about it later.
First, like many people, I assumed that, now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman History at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of the book “Boredom: A Lively History” published in 2011 by Yale University Press, does not.
“In fact, the story of boredom is very extensive,” he says.
In the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin on boredom dating from the 1st century AD.
We should also consider how we define boredom.
“The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in very different ways,” says John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing published research and putting the idea to a 100-person discussion group, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of “desiring, but not being able to, participate in an activity that fills you.”
He claims that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person does not do something but wants to do it.
It points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is “the alteration of the attention process, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly.”
Boring can sound awfully like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that although they may be related, people who are bored tend to view the problem as an issue of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be theirs.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, when what really happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues referred to a previous experiment in which participants listened to a tape from a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups listened in the adjoining room to a full-volume television show that did not keep any relationship, others listened to it with the low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the low-volume program showed more boredom than the other two groups; it cost them to concentrate, but they weren’t sure why and attributed it to boredom.
“When you try to focus on a difficult or interesting task, distracting attention can lead to boredom,” said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the study’s authors.
“On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, like detecting defective parts on a manufacturing line, a music that distracts you can help you not to get bored.”
“In fact, we now know that moving or snoring, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight it, as they make that person physically more alert.”
“Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to remain silent,” says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it’s like to get bored at some point: the delay of an airplane, a monotonous speaker, an especially boring movie.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed in the 1980s a "scale of tendency to boredom".
The scale includes issues such as “many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous” and “there are so many things that interest me that I don’t have time to do everything.”
Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external and more varied stimulation.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents between seven and eight times a day through a search.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored while at school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when not at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that “teenage is a period when boredom reaches its highest levels,” largely because both children and teens are not given much control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: Is it good to get bored?
Sometimes it is not, because, taken to the extreme, it can cause us to expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as making bets or falling into the consumption of substances as a method of combating it, as evidenced by research.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
“Burning is the brain’s way of telling you that you should be doing something else,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what’s most appropriate.
If you are bored and use that energy to play the guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch television, it may satisfy you in the short term, but not in the long term.
“So, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he may not be bored anymore, but he will not have learned to entertain himself or to do so,” says Professor Fenske.
And “that ability to dosed applies to other situations,” he notes.
Your child not only learns to entertain himself, but also learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don’t think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn’t be too critical of him either.
Our goal should be, rather, to feel comfortable away from the constant rumor of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“In our view, we need to get bored more, but boredom is a desire too distressing and disturbing as to relate it to something that’s worth it,” he says.
It points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated,” he says, “it’s hard to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops.”
