Petronella Wyatt: "They harassed me to the point of throwing me out of Oxford for being a Tory"
Students are not attacked for their views only now
I don’t remember any time in my life when I wasn’t dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been in what I assumed was the best place in the world to learn, a Greek symposium of the contemporary era that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thought and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of occupying my seat at Worcester College in the late 1980s to race the History race, I had already made the suitcases, triggering the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and started to cry.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I had left because I did not tolerate some college mates having sex in the next room.
Writer A. N. Wilson announced jokingly that I had left because they forced me to drink in uncooked cups.
The truth was less fun.
Get out of there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my extravagant name, nor the fact that it came from a private school.
I was harassed for one reason only, that in the cradle of the supposed illustration was something intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the conservative party.
Maybe they're wondering what that's all about now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of right-center students is suffering a similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred of students of the Conservative Party is such in Oxford that, last week, a group of them claimed the same level of equal rights as homosexuals, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Corpus Christi College (JCR) group of students say they are “often seriously separated, personally attacked and treated as non-gratified people” for their political ideas.
They want to create a position on your college’s Equal Opportunity Committee to make sure you can express your opinions freely.
His situation was not favoured by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" (Paradise: Young, Bright and Right) on student politics and which featured the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
He showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Party (OUCA) Association, in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a stick with a silver handle.
In other universities, conservative students say they are treated as “Turkish heads” by the introduction of higher tuition rates.
Luke Black, 20, and vice president of the Nottingham University Conservative Party Association, said in a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing leftist trend in universities.
People assume we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other.”
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who presented the motion for greater protection, says this environment is “uncomfortable,” while Stephanie Cherill, 19-year-old OUCA president-elect, says JCR members’ attitude toward people who are centre-right has worsened.
“This poses a threat to the environment of intellectual debate, as well as to the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford I was more alone than one.
I entered college in September 1986, I was an 18-year-old terribly shy.
Hatred for the Conservative Party was at its highest point.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, a title "honoris causa" after cuts in funding for Higher Education.
The atmosphere would have shocked any Stalinist.
Already during the first days of the welcome week to the new university students, when the new students meet and meet the professors, I received a sample of the bitterness that awaited me.
I discovered that not only did the professors look fat in the face of the mold that was made of conservative university students, but they participated in it with good will.
The policy of the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s opposition to apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached the seminary’s wooden rooms.
The first French texts of the 18th century were to be translated into English and I was not prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said the late Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
Not the first one.
Pitt, a low-minded man with a face that looked like a piece of cake, knew how to throw out bad bile.
“Is it thatcherists refuse to learn French or is it that they are simply stupid?” he asked.
The other students laughed.
My eyes were burning from the tears I was trying to contain.
"I suggest you go to French classes in your spare time, as long as you're not too busy meeting people," Pitt said.
I returned to my room as a grieving soul.
That night I sat alone at dinner in college; then I felt a slight palm on my back.
He was a second-year English student named James who presented himself as a member of the OUCA.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
"I'm afraid that's how it goes.
They get along with anyone who is suspected of being Tory.
It's very complicated for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it'll be even worse for you.
Many newly arrived Tories appear to be laborists.”
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to hide.
I insisted that I disagree with everything Mrs. Thatcher said.
That trick turned out to be useless.
A first-year student of Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contaminated."
Other students adopted this song.
I turned into the twisted dirt.
“How do the Tories have sex?” one asked.
“They beat each other, didn’t they?”
I felt the same way that homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could you ever live a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to stay with people who thought like me only after dark?
Would I have to become a labourer and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me were presented as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History destined for my college.
They hated him for being not only of the Conservative Party, but also Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of the people who wrote his speeches to him.
I was barely there.
He hated the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-deterministic view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a chair at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he said.
I started to travel daily from Oxford to my parents’ home in London, finding refuge in my family and friends of more open metropolitan mentality.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But if it's the best place in the world," he said sadly.
"They would never do that, not there among my beloved dream needles.
Even my communist friends have always had an impeccable attitude.”
His painful eyes began to cloud.
"Give him another chance.
I'm sure they did it just to joke.
My heart would break if you let it go.”
Tired of so many trips to London, my emotional resistance was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and had renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another History professor had hinted, speaking totally seriously, that I was an "enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Red with shame on the inside, I admitted that my parents had "washed my brain" and called them "stupid old men."
The truce lasted a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my college career in Oxford.
By that time my father was writing two weekly columns in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked with a key.
I was in a frenzy of fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left I made the suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Maybe you called me a weak lorona.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, who has not only trained 14 Conservative Party prime ministers but, to this day, is hiding behind an undeserving reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to notoriety"
