Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became world famous for his central role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, malicious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
I was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday afternoon from cancer complications, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the "Dallas" production house.
“Larry was back in her beloved Dallas hometown, again representing the iconic role she liked the most,” the family said.
Larry’s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played her wife's role in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when she died in a Dallas hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
It brought joy to everyone I knew.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an original person and lived life to the fullest,” Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and admitted that he had been drinking a lot for years.
In 1995 he was found to have a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a transplant.
Years before "Dallas", Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie", broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is altered when he finds an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and takes her to live with him at his home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971–72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included well-received roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the charmingly hateful J.R. that led Hagman to his maximum stardom.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its orbit aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional phrase “Who shot J.R.?”, designed to generate expectation around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman’s character is nearly killed, generated international speculation and millions of dollars risked in gambling houses.
He also helped give the series a record audience at the time.
When the response was revealed in a November 1980 chapter, an average of 41 million viewers tuned it and made Dallas the second most-watched entertainment program in history, behind the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. got her pregnant and then threatened to cut her off as a prostitute unless she left town, but others also had reasons to attack him.
Hagman portrayed Ewing as an insatiable corrupt with a charismatic smile: a treacherous businessman and an unfaithful husband who tried to have his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), interned.
“I know what I want in J.R.’s tombstone,” Hagman said in 1988.
He should say, "Here lies the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only deal he has lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled on Friday Hagman as someone "enormous, inside and out of the screen."
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans in the world, and in the hearts of each of us, that we were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success for the TNT channel.
