Start a course that explores the "End of the World"
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible yearning: The end of the "long countdown" of the Mayan Calendar, December 21, to which many people have been clinging as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charme had no idea what he expected in the next couple of months: Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal precipice that some have called "debtmagedon" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where late-time Christian theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
“I didn’t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester there has been,” Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If you analyze what has been going on in the world today as if we were 30 days and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those of apocalyptic mentality.
And he’s not the only teacher who offers courses on the “end of the world” this semester, in theory the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course “Media, Culture and the End of the World”.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze why these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month the students analyzed films with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
“I have tried to inform students about what is possible, likely, credible and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an associate professor of Art History and Anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled “The End of the World.”
"We don't add '2012' to always count on the option to teach the course again, in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the “imminent ruin,” students must study, generate projects, and take final exams.
In Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work “until the same night the world is supposed to end,” Restall said.
The courses were quite popular.
“It saturated in two hours,” Restall said of his high-average student course, which was filled with 35 students.
We received e-mail messages for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
The students, for their part, say that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,” said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old career student in Religion and Sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers-Camden.
And it is that the apocalyptic, secular or religious mentality is only a matter of comfort or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing career student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic films.
“I had never heard of a class that could teach that,” he said.
I'm enjoying it.
But no student interviewed — let alone a teacher — said they believed in the December 21 deadline.
“Our first project dealt with the Mayan prophecy and in a way we discredited it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old last-year student at Temple and West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it’s just a key point on the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, dating back several centuries, in which people react to the changes around them predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a surge of speculation.
“Otherwise people don’t think about it,” he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly responded to the question of whether he knew about any course on the “end of the world” there.
“The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world,” he wrote, insinuating an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many days of final judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will start thinking immediately on the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they were planning to go to “the end of the world” parties.
“Maybe call some friends so we can laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
